## Migration: `TimedExecutor` → .NET 8

### Pattern Identified: **Timeout enforcement**

Your code uses `Thread.Abort()` to kill a thread that exceeds a deadline. In .NET 6+, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — it simply doesn't work. The fix is **cooperative cancellation** with `CancellationTokenSource.CancelAfter`.

---

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);

        try
        {
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }

    // Preferred: async overload for modern callers
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout, CancellationToken externalToken = default)
    {
        using var cts = CancellationTokenSource.CreateLinkedTokenSource(externalToken);
        cts.CancelAfter(timeout);

        var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);

        try
        {
            return await task.WaitAsync(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (!externalToken.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        // If externalToken caused cancellation, OperationCanceledException propagates as-is
    }
}
```

---

### What Changed and Why

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `new Thread(...)` + `thread.Start()` | `Task.Run(work, token)` | Uses the thread pool; avoids manual thread management |
| `thread.Join(timeout)` | `task.WaitAsync(token)` | Cancellable wait — `.WaitAsync()` is new in .NET 6 |
| `thread.Abort()` | `cts.Cancel()` (implicit via timeout) | Cooperative cancellation replaces forcible abort |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` | The new exception type for cancellation |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Removed | No equivalent needed — cancellation doesn't auto-rethrow |

---

### ⚠️ Critical Pitfall: Uncooperative Work

The **fundamental limitation** of cooperative cancellation: if `work` doesn't check the token, it keeps running even after the timeout fires. Your original `Thread.Abort()` could forcibly terminate it — `CancellationToken` cannot.

**If `work` is code you control**, accept and check the token:

```csharp
// Pass the token into work so it can cooperate
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    var token = cts.Token;
    var task = Task.Run(() => work(token), token);

    try
    {
        return task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}

// The work cooperates by checking the token:
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in largeCollection)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return "done";
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

**If `work` is uncooperative code you can't modify** (third-party library, long-running native call), the only true equivalent of `Thread.Abort` is to run it in a **separate process** and call `Process.Kill()` on timeout. There is no in-process alternative in modern .NET.

---

### Other Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Mitigation |
|---|---|
| **Forgetting `using` on `CancellationTokenSource`** | It's `IDisposable` — leaking it leaks timers. Always `using`. |
| **`Thread.Sleep` in work ignores the token** | Replace with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` or `await Task.Delay(ms, token)` |
| **Swallowing `OperationCanceledException`** | Only catch it at the top level to convert to `TimeoutException`. Let it propagate otherwise. |
| **Sync-over-async deadlocks** | The sync `ExecuteWithTimeout` calls `.GetAwaiter().GetResult()`. Safe here because `Task.Run` offloads to the thread pool, but prefer the `async` overload when possible. |
